So this is our example
local video player.

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:57.520
And wow, I probably could have
taken up more space on the

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.360
screen than just that.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:03.040
But this is our example
video that we have.

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:07.010
This is an example video player
that just, again, local

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:11.170
content, and it shows you
a couple of things.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:14.220
And basically, the rough
structure of this app is that

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:17.510
you could imagine that you've
categorized your local videos

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:19.890
into different groups
or categories.

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:21.240
We'll show that in a second.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:25.130
And then you might have a queue
of a local videos that

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.480
you plan on watching.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.650
And then you probably want to
have some sort of sense of

00:03:30.650 --> 00:03:34.615
what has been recently added,
what are recently looked at

00:03:34.615 --> 00:03:37.450
or, whatever has been
added in the device.

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:40.300
So this screen is this kind of
your up next screen, which is

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:43.700
kind of like a dashboard
or home screen.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:47.630
And we chose here to showcase
the two probably most

00:03:47.630 --> 00:03:50.660
important things-- in my
opinion, at least--

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:54.010
for local video playback and for
general media consumption

00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:55.800
is what's up next, right?

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.000
Either stuff that I've recently
added or stuff that

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.630
I've explicitly added
to a queue.

00:04:00.630 --> 00:04:02.920
Now, you notice that there are
a couple things you can do

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:04.490
with this queue.

00:04:04.490 --> 00:04:05.906
You can first--

00:04:05.906 --> 00:04:06.740
uh-oh.

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:07.290
Actually, oh, my mouse
is moving.

00:04:07.290 --> 00:04:09.312
That's what it is.

00:04:09.312 --> 00:04:10.076
[CHUCKLES]

00:04:10.076 --> 00:04:15.730
You can first reorder the queue
items by using this

00:04:15.730 --> 00:04:18.500
dragging affordance to the
left of each list item.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:21.120
This is something that again,
that you could find in the

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:26.400
Google Play Music App within a
playlist to reorder tracks.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:28.760
And then below the queue,
there's the

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:30.910
recently added list.

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:33.840
And it's not really a
list as it is more

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:35.910
like a set of tiles.

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:37.360
You've seen this several
times in the show.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:41.620
We use this presentation of
content fairly frequently

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:43.070
because it's very versatile.

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:45.850
It works across different
device sizes.

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:48.930
It works across different aspect
ratios of content.

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:52.680
It's, in general, very,
very versatile.

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:56.370
What I wanted to point out here
is that there's a lot you

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:59.570
can do with this tile area, and
it's going to be really

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:00.750
hard to show here.

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:02.530
Let's see if this works.

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:06.470
So zooming in on my laptop does
not work, unfortunately.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:08.980
But there's a lot of detail
in these tiles.

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:13.480
If you look at the top right
tile in Recently Added, you

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:16.390
notice that there's a little
status indicator, indicating

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:18.270
that something is
in the queue.

00:05:18.270 --> 00:05:20.120
So this is something that--

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:23.850
again, you can use this for
starring or bookmarking or, in

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:25.740
this case, queueing.

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:29.640
It's a good, nice, little,
non-interactive indicator that

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:30.525
this is a special item.

00:05:30.525 --> 00:05:32.850
And in this case, it really
means this is

00:05:32.850 --> 00:05:34.120
already in your queue.

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:38.010
This is just like you would
see in like Gmail or such.

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:39.220
If something is starred,
it has an

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:42.190
indicator in the playlist.

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:46.390
The other thing is that you
can swipe to dismiss items

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:47.250
from the queue.

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:50.940
So we're not really using a
horizontal swipe for anything

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:52.690
else on this screen.

00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:56.690
And even if we were, we'd be
able to still use bezel swipe

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.760
to access adjacent
lateral content.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.190
But in this case, a queue is
something that naturally lends

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:04.700
itself to swipe to dismiss.

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:08.060
So you can dismiss items, get
rid of them off of your queue

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:10.860
by just swiping them away.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:12.380
Before we move on to
other screens,

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:14.855
anything thoughts, guys?

00:06:14.855 --> 00:06:16.350
NICK BUTCHER: Personally,
I think

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:17.670
it's a very nice treatment.

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:20.820
I think a problem with a lot of
these video-playing apps is

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:22.770
they seem to concentrate a lot
on the video playback, which

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:23.200
is awesome.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:24.220
I mean, it's the core utility.

00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:28.510
But then they don't make a
huge amount of effort to

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:32.040
follow any design guidelines
for the file

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:34.216
management type tasks.

00:06:34.216 --> 00:06:37.780
It seems like there's a lot of
apps like in the early 90s

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:39.570
when everyone was building
Winamp skins.

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:42.430
It's all about the visual bling
and then like having

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:45.207
17,000 different format
playbacks, but then no effort

00:06:45.207 --> 00:06:48.060
is being spent on the thing that
actually gets you to into

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:48.820
that presence.

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:50.355
So I really like the
treatment here.

00:06:50.355 --> 00:06:51.760
Especially I like the key
management features with the

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:52.935
swipe to dismiss.

00:06:52.935 --> 00:06:55.820
I think that really works
very well here.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:59.490
ADAM KOCH: and I guess I kind of
like how queue is given the

00:06:59.490 --> 00:07:02.940
priority here, and it's a sort
of infinitely growing list, so

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.160
there can be a ton of
items in your queue.

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:07.730
And then below that, you've got
Recently Added, which may

00:07:07.730 --> 00:07:10.515
not be as important, but kind of
nice to browse, and you can

00:07:10.515 --> 00:07:13.610
possibly add those items
straight to your queue, which

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.916
then gets that mass or
indicator, which we're always

00:07:15.916 --> 00:07:17.035
talking about.

00:07:17.035 --> 00:07:18.420
ROMAN NURIK: It's actually
very similar to

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:19.810
the People app, too.

00:07:19.810 --> 00:07:23.320
In the People app, you have
your Favorites tab.

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:26.020
And in your Favorites tab, you
have the top items, which are

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:28.746
your starred people or your
favorite people, kind of like

00:07:28.746 --> 00:07:29.820
your quick dial.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:34.060
Then below that, in case you
haven't favorited anybody, or

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.620
even if you have, it's kind
of like extra content.

00:07:36.620 --> 00:07:38.980
It's kind of below the fold.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:42.090
It's not as important as your
favorites, but your recent or

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:44.880
frequently called people or
frequently contacted people

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:46.220
are also something that
you probably want

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:47.012
to have access to.

00:07:47.012 --> 00:07:50.020
ADAM KOCH: Yeah, and then if
your queue is getting kind of

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:52.040
short, there's not that many
items in it, then you

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:54.490
instantly can see those recently
added items if you

00:07:54.490 --> 00:07:56.398
want to add something
to it, too.

00:07:56.398 --> 00:07:58.020
ROMAN NURIK: Exactly.

