00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:12.510
Crouton is a--

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:15.260
initially I think it came from
a blog post by Mr. Cyril

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:18.270
Mottier, who had some
frustrations with the Android

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:22.470
toast class, which is a way
of giving these transitive

00:29:22.470 --> 00:29:25.660
messages that show up after a
little while and disappear.

00:29:25.660 --> 00:29:28.200
But some of the limitations of
it were annoying him in that

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.460
it wasn't really attached
to an activity.

00:29:30.460 --> 00:29:32.615
So if you were to show a toast
message and then switch away

00:29:32.615 --> 00:29:35.320
to another activity, the message
may remain and be out

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:36.240
of context.

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:39.790
So he has come up with a
toast-like API for showing

00:29:39.790 --> 00:29:43.140
more contextual messages, so you
can have info messages and

00:29:43.140 --> 00:29:45.320
error messages and so on
within the flow of the

00:29:45.320 --> 00:29:46.260
application.

00:29:46.260 --> 00:29:48.740
So he outlined this in a blog
placement, but actually

00:29:48.740 --> 00:29:49.660
couldn't read any code.

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:52.470
I think the IP was owned
by his employer.

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:57.110
So Mr. Benjamin Vice, another
Berlin hacker, has taken this

00:29:57.110 --> 00:29:59.600
idea and run with it and
open-sourced the Crouton

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:01.620
library, which you can
find on GitHub.

00:30:01.620 --> 00:30:03.970
And it's in active development
and getting their

00:30:03.970 --> 00:30:05.186
contributions and stars.

00:30:05.186 --> 00:30:08.050
And I encourage you to take
a look at it, and it might

00:30:08.050 --> 00:30:09.610
provide you a nice
way to get these

00:30:09.610 --> 00:30:12.096
contextual in-app messages.

00:30:12.096 --> 00:30:13.090
ROMAN NURIK: All right.

00:30:13.090 --> 00:30:13.730
And is that it?

00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:17.840
No, we have one more from
